title: Russia in 'far worse position now' than during 2022 talks | Michael Clarke analysis
description:
Russia is in a "far worse position now" compared to 2022, when direct negotiations with Ukraine last took place, security and defence analyst, Professor Michael Clarke, has been telling Sky News. 

Speaking with talks between Russia and Ukraine underway in Istanbul, Clarke said: "Compared to 2022, the Russians are in a far worse position now than they were then because in 2022, they thought, 'it's only a matter of time before we take the whole country'. "

Read more: https://news.sky.com/story/ukraine-war-latest-peace-talks-zelenskyy-putin-istanbul-crimea-baltic-nato-jet-clarke-frontline-turkey-erdogan-12541713

text:
Russia in 'far worse position now' than during 2022 talks | Michael Clarke analysis

Russia is in a "far worse position now" compared to 2022, when direct negotiations with Ukraine last took place, security and defence analyst, Professor Michael Clarke, has been telling Sky News. 

Speaking with talks between Russia and Ukraine underway in Istanbul, Clarke said: "Compared to 2022, the Russians are in a far worse position now than they were then because in 2022, they thought, 'it's only a matter of time before we take the whole country'. "

title: Satellite images show Putin massing Russian troops on border with Finland
description:
Satellite images show Putin building up a substantial military presence on the Finnish border.

Images obtained by Swedish broadcaster SVT show four locations have seen a significant increase in activity.

NATO member Finland heavily protects its eastern border.

In 2022, a border fence was erected to provide more defence against a Russian invasion.

Following Finlandâ€™s accession to NATO, Kremlin officials threatened â€˜military-technical response measuresâ€™.

This move shows a worrying war stance being adopted by Putin on Russiaâ€™s north-east border.

Ukrainian Ambassador Oleksii Makeiev has welcomed the decision of the new German government to treat arms deliveries to Ukraine as a secret matter again. "A good chess player thinks several moves ahead. What he doesn't do is predict these moves to his opponent," Makeiev told the German Press Agency. "As ambassador of Ukraine, I am privy to such secrets," he added. After Chancellor Friedrich Merz's visit to Kyiv, he was therefore able to confirm: "Germany will deliver. And we know exactly what and when. And we are satisfied." The former Ukrainian ambassador, Andriy Melnyk, had previously criticized Merz for the return to secrecy. "This brings back bad memories of the time when the traffic light government tried to conceal a lack of military support in the spring of 2022 with secrecy," he said.

title: Russia urgently "cancels May 9" after massive Ukrainian drone attack
description:
#Kanal13â€‹ #likekanal13â€‹ #subscribekanal13 #warinukraine
https://www.youtube.com/user/kanal13az?sub_confirmation=1 - SUBSCRIBE TO US!
The aggressor country is urgently changing its plans regarding propaganda events timed to coincide with May 9. Following the massive attack by Ukrainian drones on Russian territory, a wave of cancellations of events planned for the said date has begun in the Russian Federation,  Verstka  writes . The restrictions affected at least Moscow, the Moscow region, the Vladimir, Lipetsk, Vologda regions and Mordovia. Thus, in Yegoryevsk, the memorial service for the victims was moved from the cemetery to the church "for safety reasons." In Ramenskoye, a school performance was cancelled, and in the Pavlovsky Posad District, evening concerts were cancelled, while car rallies and flower-laying ceremonies were retained. In the Vladimir region, the Immortal Regiment march and an evening concert have been cancelled in Kirzhach due to the "threat of a UAV crash". Similar measures have been taken in the Lipetsk region, where events have been postponed indefinitely and some events have been transferred to an online format. In Mordovia, the gala concert has been postponed to May 15 â€“ officially due to "Internet restrictions." In the Vologda Region, bad weather was cited as the reason for postponing the events. In addition, performances by Russian artists who were unable to fly out of the Russian capital due to flight delays are being cancelled. 

Recall, Russiaâ€™s Defense Ministry has claimed its air defenses destroyed about 524 Ukrainian drones in a single day during what it called the most massive drone attack to date. The figure came after pro-war Russian military bloggers reported a record drone and missile assault on Russia overnight into May 7. The Z-affiliated Telegram channel Voevoda Veshchaet stated that 447 long-range drones and missiles had struck Russia between the evening of May 6 and early hours of May 7. The bloggers described it as the largest drone attack since the start of Russiaâ€™s full-scale invasion of Ukraine. During the night, Russian Telegram channels tracked swarms of drones headed toward Moscow via Ryazan, Tula and Oryol oblasts. Residents in the Moscow suburbs of Yegoryevsk and Kolomna reported hearing the sound of UAVs and explosions.

By morning, Russian airlines had begun mass cancellations and flight mergers, citing disruptions caused by the drone attacks.

Andrii Kovalenko, head of Ukraineâ€™s Center for Counteracting Disinformation at the National Security and Defense Council, said a number of high-value targets within Russiaâ€™s military-industrial complex had been hit.

In Saransk, a fiber-optic systems plant was struck. In Tula, the attack targeted the Instrument Design Bureau. Another target was the Splav enterprise, a key developer of multiple launch rocket systems for the Russian military.

title: North Korea confirms it sent troops to fight for Russia in Ukraine war | BBC News
description:
North Korea has for the first time confirmed that it sent troops to fight for Russia against Ukraine.
 
In a report on state news agency KCNA, Pyongyang's military claimed its soldiers helped Russian forces "completely liberate" the Kursk border region, according to an order given by leader Kim Jong Un.
 
Pyongyang's announcement comes just days after Russian Chief of Staff Valery Gerasimov praised the "heroism" of North Korean troops, the first time Moscow has publicly acknowledged their involvement.
 
Western officials had earlier told the BBC they believed at least 1,000 of the 11,000 troops sent from North Korea had been killed over three months.

North Korea confirms it sent troops to fight for Russia in Ukraine war | BBC News

North Korea has for the first time confirmed that it sent troops to fight for Russia against Ukraine.
 
In a report on state news agency KCNA, Pyongyang's military claimed its soldiers helped Russian forces "completely liberate" the Kursk border region, according to an order given by leader Kim Jong Un.
 
Pyongyang's announcement comes just days after Russian Chief of Staff Valery Gerasimov praised the "heroism" of North Korean troops, the first time Moscow has publicly acknowledged their involvement.
 
Western officials had earlier told the BBC they believed at least 1,000 of the 11,000 troops sent from North Korea had been killed over three months.

Alik Bakhshi

A slowpoke from the White House

Donald Trump, literally in the first days of his presidency, promised to stop the bloodshed in Ukraine and save thousands of people from death. As a thrifty owner and businessman, for whom America is above all else, Trump was concerned about America's spending on military aid to Ukraine. He did not care at all under what conditions the war would stop and a peace treaty would be signed between the aggressor and the victim. I believe Trump planned to benefit from the peace agreement between Russia and Ukraine. Having already had experience communicating with Putin, and apparently knowing him as a smart and calculating politician, Trump decided to put pressure on Zelensky first and invited him to the White House in the hope that under the threat of ending military aid, he would be able to persuade the young green politician to make concessions. However, Trump was very wrong, Zelensky surprisingly turned out to be a tough nut to crack, who made it clear to the American businessman that he was not going to trade Ukrainian territory.

However, Zelensky's unsuccessful visit also had a positive side for Ukraine, because against the backdrop of Trump's threat to interrupt arms supplies to Ukraine, EU countries realized the need to ensure Ukraine's victory in its war with fascist Russia on their own. And after three months, Trump also realized the futility of simply persuading to end the bloodshed. Moreover, in order not to look like a lost sheep, Trump abandoned his threat to suspend arms supplies to Ukraine. At the same time, on May 12, European leaders and Trump issued an ultimatum demanding a ceasefire along the entire front line for 30 days and to begin peace talks without delay, otherwise tougher sanctions would be imposed on Russia. Trump promised to transfer weapons to Ukraine in quantities sufficient to defeat the Russian army if Putin refused direct negotiations.

It seems that this time Putin, who had been counting on a split between America and the EU, was seriously scared for the first time, so much so that without waiting for the next day, he urgently gathered his servants at 2 a.m. and announced his intention to start direct negotiations with Ukraine on May 15 in Istanbul. However, Putin did not say a word about a 30-day truce. Zelensky, in turn, immediately announced his readiness for a personal meeting with Putin. Here Putin, without expecting it, fell into a trap that he himself had set. It must be said that Putin avoided any debates and, unlike other presidential contenders, never took part in them during the election campaign. It is not difficult to foresee that during a face-to-face meeting, the former comedian showman will devour him alive, especially in the presence of Erdogan and Trump himself, who could not miss an opportunity to get some extra PR, who made him want to fly to such a significant event. Such a prospect was clearly not in the calculation of the Kremlin dictator. Well, what can he tell the whole world - I want war? After all, only war, and preferably a victorious one, reliably ensures his stay on the royal throne. Peace in the current circumstances is like death for Putin. The Russian people, impoverished by the war, with their imperial worldview, will not forgive the Fuhrer for his unfulfilled dreams of reviving the empire and the many thousands of soldiers who died in vain. Naturally, Putin at the last moment refused to meet with Zelensky and belatedly sent negotiators to Istanbul who do not have any authority, with the sole purpose of dragging out these negotiations for as long as possible.

How this childishly naive trick of Putin will be perceived depends entirely on Trump, who, I hope, will finally understand his mistake in thinking that the war can be stopped through negotiations without defeating the aggressor. Trump could have really saved thousands of lives if, upon entering the White House, he had not repeated Biden's mistake of supplying weapons in small doses, but had immediately ordered the transfer of weapons to Ukraine in the quantities necessary for victory. Only a convincing victory for Ukraine can thwart Putin's revanchist plans to restore the Russian Empire within the borders of the Soviet Union.

In abrams the ammunition is stored in the rear part of the turret. When it ignites,  the energy is released through special hatches. In russian tanks due to the usage of autoloader, the ammunition is stored in a carousel around the turret so it all explodes launching the turret up in the air. Let's clarify that russian tanks were designed with a different tactics in mind where during cold war they assumed that they need a swarm of cheap small tanks that would push forward in waves regardless of the loses. If crew and vehicles are disposable, that would be a valid tactic at that time. But not when you use them as infantry support in small numbers. Those are zergs, not protons.

4:37 To be fair, it is entirely the fault of the auto loader design in these Russian tanks that causes this. Leopards and Abrams tanks can have a separated ammo compartment so that if it goes up in flames the chances of the crew being affected is minimal. But because the Russian tanks use a carousel type autoloader it is impossible to separate the crew entirely from the ammo (at least in most cases) because it's usually right behind or under the turret basket. There are 3 different fire events.  One is the fuel.  It is diesel and stored both internally, and externally.  You can see it leaking on the ground , on fire, running downhill.  Fire suppression systems have a chance putting out this fire.  The next is 'gunpowder', or more correctly, a propellent fire.  This is signaled by the 'blowtorch flames' shooting out the tank.  Russian tanks have this inside the crew compartment, not isolated like the Abrams, etc.  Once this conflagration starts, it feeds on the next piece of ammunition.  The crew has mere moments to get out.  Fire suppression is not helpful.  The worst event is the detonation of the ammunition's projectiles.  The High Explosive in both HE and HEAT shells evidently can 'cook off' from both a propellent fire, or being actually struck by a penetration, or sympathetically from a drones explosion.  This leads to a triple event of fuel, propellant, and high explosives all getting consumed and the vehicle being ripped apart, and turrets, etc. flying about.  In WWII, the Soviets used very sensitive explosives in their shells.  I would bet they still do.  I don't see how any Russian can serve in an armored vehicle at this point.

At the time of Ukraineâ€™s independence from the Soviet Union in 1991, Ukraine held the third largest nuclear arsenal in the world, including an estimated 1,900 strategic warheads, 176 intercontinental ballistic missiles (ICBMs), and 44 strategic bombers. By 1996, Ukraine had returned all of its nuclear warheads to Russia in exchange for economic aid and security assurances, and in December 1994, Ukraine became a non-nuclear weapon state-party to the 1968 nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty (NPT). The last strategic nuclear delivery vehicle in Ukraine was eliminated in 2001 under the 1991 Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty (START). It took years of political maneuvering and diplomatic work, starting with the Lisbon Protocol in 1992, to remove the weapons and nuclear infrastructure from Ukraine.

Putin and Zelensky have not met in person since December 2019. Russia and Ukraine last held direct negotiations in March 2022 in Istanbul, shortly after Moscow launched its full-scale invasion of its neighbour.

Fighting has raged in Ukraine since then. Russian forces have slowly expanded the amount of territory they control over the past year, mostly in the east of Ukraine.

Putin had initially called for direct talks between Russia and Ukraine in Turkey's largest city "without pre-conditions", before Zelensky announced that he would go in person and expected the Russian president to travel as well.

Putin's suggestion of direct talks in Istanbul followed Western powers' call for a 30-day ceasefire, after European leaders met in Kyiv on Saturday.

After Trump called for Ukraine to accept the offer on Sunday, Zelensky said he would travel there himself.

A historic summit between Russian President Vladimir Putin and Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky could be on the horizon, as Moscow signals its willingness to meet if concrete agreements are reached in ongoing peace talks. Following the first direct negotiations between Russia and Ukraine since 2022-held in Istanbul and mediated by Turkey-Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov stated that a Putin-Zelensky meeting is possible, but only after both sidesâ€™ delegations finalize specific terms. **War Between Russia and Poland: Historical Context**

The war between Russia and Poland lasted for 196 years â€” from the 15th to the 17th century. Formally, the conflict never truly ended, despite numerous truces that sometimes lasted 5, 10, or even 25 years. These truces were merely pauses in a single, prolonged war that continued until Russia achieved its goals.

This is important to take into account when understanding the historical specifics and when building any kind of strategy. Expecting that Russia will â€œgrow tiredâ€ and retreat is a profoundly unhistorical forecast. Of course, history does include unique and unexpected cases â€” no one rules out the emergence of catastrophes or extraordinary events. But based on historical experience, this particular feature of Russian strategy deserves attention and respect.

In a significant development, Russian President Vladimir Putin has offered Ukraine the opportunity to restart peace talks without preconditions, proposing Turkey as the meeting venue. In response, Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky has expressed a desire for a ceasefire and welcomed Putin to Turkey for dialogues. Both leaders have not met face-to-face since 2019, raising questions about the feasibility of these peace talks.Â

title: Russian drone attack on Ukraine bus kills nine, officials say | BBC News
description:
Local officials say nine people have been killed in a Russian drone attack on a civilian bus in north-eastern Ukraine.

The Sumy regional military administration said four other people were injured in the town of Bilopillia on Saturday morning as the bus travelled to the regional capital Sumy, close to Russia's border. 

The reported attack comes just hours after Russia and Ukraine held their first direct peace talks since 2022 - no breakthrough was achieved, although a swap of prisoners of war was agreed. 

Ukraine's national police described the bus attack as a "cynical war crime". Russia has not commented directly but said it had hit a "military staging area" in Sumy.

Subscribe here: http://bit.ly/1rbfUog

For more news, analysis and features visit: www.bbc.com/news 

#Ukraine #BBCNews

Poland annexing any Ukrainian territory is something that is extremely hard to imagine. Recognizing Ukraineâ€™s territory in full was practically an unquestionable foreign policy of any Polish government since the moment Poland become free from the Soviet control. The idea of relinquishing Polandâ€™s claim over the Galicia and Volhynia, that were annexed into the Soviet Ukraine after the WWII, was thought out by the Polish emigres for, among other reasons, a way to settle the question of Polandâ€™s Western borders that similarly moved to the West into the previously German-controlled territory after the war. No less importantly, Polish intellectuals saw a need to have a strong Ukraine as a way to counter a potential threat from Russia. (Look up Juliusz Mieroszewski and Jerzy Giedroyc)

From time to time one can read news about Ukraine and Poland arguing with each other about their shared history, I know that history does not like hypotheticals, but I think it is nothing in comparison to what these relations could have been without the Polish-Ukrainian reconciliation that has happened throughout the years. You got to remember that prior to that in the XX century the Polish-Ukrainian conflicts were brutal, there was an enormous amount of mutual animosity.

24:30  I don't think that's what happened there. 
Itâ€™s actually pretty standard for small team assault to use APCs, IFVs, or even tanks(*) to provide covering fire for their advance and then just seemingly abandoning the troops after they've dismounted and entered the position.
(*sometimes on bigger assaults they are just riding on top of the vehicle: funnily enough it's often seen on BTRs since it's really a death trap to stay in it because of the little amount armor, it's still used because of the stabed 30mm of the 82a or just when there's nothing else, from what i've seen ukraine doesn't use it much anymore an assault but more as a gun on wheels and other variants maybe for rotations since it's better than a pickup).

Anyway the reason the vehicules rarely stays is to not attract arty, drones or RPGs coming from others trenches, they'll usually retreat a few hundred meters waiting to be used for casevac.
It looks very dangerous and crude but the tactic let the vehicle suppress enemy positions during the rapid advance, and let the troops riding it dismount very close to trenches or strongpoints fairly safely. 

The â€œstranded infantry left behind after a vehicle is hit and retreat aloneâ€ yeah, it can happen, but what people often complain about is when a vehicleâ€™s knocked out mid-assault and other vehicle accompanying the assault don't pick the stranded infantry up and justleave the areaâ€¦ but well, warâ€™s messy.

title: Peace talks between Ukraine and Russia take place in Turkey | BBC News
description:
Officials from Ukraine and Russia will meet today in Istanbul, Turkey for peace talks.
 
Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky is attending the negotiations, but criticised the "low-level" delegation being sent by Moscow as Russian President Vladimir Putin will not be there.
 
US President Donald Trump suggested that significant progress in peace talks was unlikely until he and Putin met in person.
 
Subscribe here: http://bit.ly/1rbfUog
 
For more news, analysis and features visit: www.bbc.com/news

There have been several rounds of peace talks to end the Russian invasion of Ukraine since it began in February 2022. Russia's president Vladimir Putin seeks recognition of all occupied land as Russian, for Russia to be given all of the regions it claims but does not fully control, guarantees that Ukraine will never join NATO, and the lifting of sanctions against Russia. Ukraine's president Volodymyr Zelenskyy seeks a full withdrawal of Russian troops, the return of prisoners and kidnapped Ukrainian children, prosecution of Russian leaders for war crimes, and security guarantees to prevent further Russian aggression.
The first meeting between Russian and Ukrainian officials took place four days after the invasion began, on 28 February 2022, in Belarus, and concluded without result. Later rounds of talks took place in March 2022 on the Belarusâ€“Ukraine border and in Antalya, Turkey. Negotiations in Turkey created an agreement in which Ukraine would abandon plans to join NATO and have limits placed on its military, while having security guarantees from Western countries, and not being required to recognize Russia's annexation of Crimea. The draft treaty was almost agreed to, but disagreements over security guarantees and the Bucha massacre ultimately halted negotiations.

title: Ukraine Is Using Robot Attack Dogs Against Russia | War on Tape | Daily Mail
description:
It looks like something out of science fiction but is in fact terrifyingly real - a robot dog being used by the Ukrainians to help fight the Russians. The Khartiia Brigade, which considers itself a model unit for the future Ukrainian army, has employed the dog on combat missions as a scout, using it to navigate minefields and map enemy trenches. 

But this is just the beginning - already, some people are experimenting with attaching weapons to it, and integrating AI would allow the dog to identify and attack its own targets. Which begs the question: Is this the future of war? Allow War on Tape to explain.

To look at it from another window:
The USA and England signaled that Ukraine could be admitted to Nato. In the face of Russia's increasing attacks, Ukraine never thought of establishing a bargaining table with Russia. Because the USA and the UK said that they would provide unlimited military ammunition and material support to Ukraine in case of war.

But 1 year after the war started, the USA cut off aid. Because the U.S. Congress wanted it that way. After encouraging Ukraine to go to war, the USA's response to Ukraine at a time when military ammunition was most needed was "the shop is closed"!!
Although it is claimed that a lot of aid has been provided, this does not reflect the truth. The only most important aid that works is Patriot missiles. The weapons sent by many EU member countries are scrap and garbage!! Some EU countries, such as Greece, Bulgaria, etc., which have old Soviet-made weapons and equipment in their inventories, sent ammunition and weapons to Ukraine that were expired, had no military value and had to be destroyed and removed from the inventory. Currently, Ukraine has turned into a dump with hundreds of types of old weapons and ammunition that have lost their destructive power.
There are a few major countries that currently send weapons.
Even though it has been 2 years since the war started, there are no F-16s yet!!
Germany refuses to provide missile aid with the excuse that its range is 500 km. Because he is worried that Ukraine may attack Russian cities with those missiles.
Europe's monetary aid is generally used to pay salaries and for civilian needs. Some useful weapons aid loses its meaning because it is not provided on time.
These people are in the middle of a war. In the harsh winter of Eastern Europe, they are trying to hunt the enemy, wrapped in the icy iron of machine guns. They are about to run out of ammunition. There is a war full of empty promises and so-called supporters who cannot find 155 mm artillery shells.
Biden cannot send the weapons he promised because he could not convince a few Republican senators!! Germany does not send missiles because it is afraid of Russia. The weapon containers that many countries boast about in the media are outdated inventory residues from the cold war period...!

On April 3, 1940, NKVD units began the systematic murder of officers and members of other elites. The assassination was initiated by then NKVD chief Lavrenti Beria. A month earlier, Beria had sent a letter to the Politburo, the governing body of the Soviet Union. In it he proposed the secret shooting of more than 25,000 prisoners of war, mostly from Poland, without any trial. These people are "declared and hopeless enemies of Soviet power," Beria wrote.
